				<div style="font-style:italic">I do not agree with the idea that some drugs should be legalized, and others shouldn't. I think all &quot;drugs&quot; should be legalized, produced and distributed by the government, regulated and taxed heavily with a hopefully goodly portion of the taxes collected going into programs that help people when they are ready to try and break from their addictions.<br />
 <br />
It is not for us to say, &quot;this drug is ok, but that one isn't.&quot; Each is a means to an end for the user. And users are not evil people, they're damaged and hurting and society has already condemned them, judged them as lesser people, and labeled them as cheaters, liars and thieves. An addict doesn't want to hurt anyone or take their things, but therein lies the terrible power of substance addiction. It hijacks otherwise good people and turns them into terrible shadows of their formal selves. And it's no wonder that 50% of all addicts relapse. What's left when you're at that point and society has written you off and put you in it's box and the shit that drove you to do the things you did in the first place hasn't gone away, but has only gotten worse.<br />
 <br />
Until we change our views and see addicts as people who need love, help, understanding and sometimes protection from themselves or from them harming others - until we stop judging them because the end result of the damage in their lives has manifested itself in a substance addiction, nothing will change. Society would rather continue to blame the user for their inability to deal with highly addictive substances, when no human could - that they are using in the first place because their reality is so aweful, or their pain is so great that the turn to these things in the first place just to cope.<br />
