		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1462567">Recently there has been a furor in the UK about ecstasy. The government appointed review body chair made the point that more people die each year in the UK from horse riding than they do from ecstasy. The board then recommended that ecstasy been down-graded as a Class A drug to a Class B drug. This would mean lighter penalties if caught with it. <br />
<br />
The government of course ignored the advice of it's own appointed board, and has kept ecstasy as a Class A drug. Now, I've never done it myself, but judging from the effects on friends I don't think ecstasy is as damaging as heroin, which is also Class A. Yet, thanks to the popular press, the government would rather be percieved to be acting tough on drugs than actually *solving* the drugs issue. <br />
<br />
Fundamentally, it's going to require a group of politicians who aren't concerned with the next election 4 years away to make some of the changes we need to make around our drugs policies. Until that happens, we'll continue pouring money and resources into fights we cannot win, that just inflict disproportionate punishment on those most vulnerable and worse off in society.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		
